As the climate data explicitly demonstrates, Culver City is generally blessed with a mild, temperate environment, largely devoid of extreme weather fluctuations. The summers are warm and dry, almost aggressively so in August and September when temperatures can peak well into the 90s Fahrenheit, occasionally breaching 100°F. Winters are characteristically mild, with daily mean temperatures comfortably in the 50s and low 60s. Precipitation, a rare commodity in Southern California, is concentrated in the cooler months, with January and February typically receiving the most rainfall. The dry season, stretching from late spring through early autumn, often sees negligible, if any, measurable [precipitation](/Precipitation). It's a climate designed for perpetually sunny dispositions, or at least, for those who appreciate consistent, unremarkable weather.

