#### Ethnic groups

According to the comprehensive data from the 2020 Census, the population of Culver City demonstrated a diverse [ethnic composition](/Ethnic_group). The largest demographic group was Non-Hispanic White individuals, accounting for 46.5% of the total population. This was followed by a significant [Asian](/Asian_Americans) population at 16.1%. [Hispanic White](/Hispanic_and_Latino_Americans) residents constituted 15.2% of the population, while [Black or African American](/African_Americans) individuals made up 8.24%. The category of "Other Hispanic" accounted for 5.57%, further illustrating the varied cultural backgrounds within the city.

Further insights into the city's ancestry and origins, as compiled by the [Mapping L.A.](/Mapping_L.A.) project, revealed that in the year 2000, the most commonly reported ancestries among Culver City residents were [Mexican](/Mexican_Americans) and [German](/German_Americans). Correspondingly, the nations of [Mexico](/Mexico) and the [Philippines](/Philippines) emerged as the most frequently cited foreign places of birth among the immigrant population, underscoring the strong ties to these countries.

## Economy

Culver City's economy, much like its history, is a dynamic blend of entertainment, technology, and service industries, reflecting its strategic position within the broader [Los Angeles](/Los_Angeles) metropolitan area. One notable presence is [NPR West](/NPR), the western production hub for [National Public Radio](/National_Public_Radio). It has maintained offices in the city since 2002, occupying a former furniture factory—a symbolic transformation from manufacturing to the dissemination of information, or at least, carefully curated soundbites.

The city serves as the corporate headquarters for a number of significant companies, solidifying its role as a modern business center. These include the audio technology giant [Beats Audio](/Beats_Audio), the cannabis retailer [MedMen](/MedMen), the healthcare technology firm [NantHealth](/NantHealth), the health-conscious restaurant chain [Sweetgreen](/Sweetgreen), and, of course, the enduring entertainment powerhouse, [Sony Pictures Entertainment](/Sony_Pictures_Entertainment).

